Consequently, there will be destruction of some tourist sites. This will definitely hamper tourism and lead to a reduction of revenue collection, considering that 65 per cent of the tourists who come to Kenya visit the coastal region.
Drastic action
Further inland, climate shifts have contributed to worsening droughts, which put a strain on the ability of even the most adaptive wildlife to cope.
In recent droughts, such as in 2009/2010, the population of elephants, zebras and wildebeests suffered huge losses in the Maasai Mara. The Kenya Wildlife service had to provide water and hay for wild animals.
These effects on game reserves and national parks, which are the main tourist attractions, will significantly affect tourist arrivals. The increase of the average annual temperature will also likely compromise or eliminate certain ecologically sensitive destinations.
For example, the depletion of glaciers on Mount Kenya and Kilimanjaro will greatly impact tourism given that the two mountains are tourist attractions due to their positions near the equator where no snow would be expected.
Another aspect of climate change that will affect tourism is floods, which affect infrastructure to tourist destinations. In 2011/2012, the road networks to the Maasai Mara were destroyed by floods rendering them impassable. Subsequently, tourist numbers fell.



